Here's the registration in `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Data service: one HttpClient/config shared app-wide
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels: new instance per navigation to avoid stale state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages: new instance per navigation so each binds a fresh VM
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why each lifetime:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Holds an `HttpClient` and shared config. One instance avoids socket exhaustion and lets you cache/share state (auth tokens, etc.) across the app. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each navigation should get a fresh VM so you never display stale data or leftover UI state from a previous visit. |
| Pages | **Transient** | Pairs with transient VMs — each page instance receives its own new VM via constructor injection. |

**When you'd use `AddScoped` instead:** In MAUI, scoped lifetime is rarely useful because there's no built-in per-request scope like in ASP.NET. Stick with singleton for shared infrastructure and transient for UI-layer objects.
